example_quotes: Medical Student: OK. Any infectious symptoms overall?
Patient: Ahh, I don't I don't think so.
Medical Student: OK. Bowel problems?
Patient: uh no, no. No, that's all good.
Medical Student: OK um. And, uh, any fevers or chills?
Patient: No.
Medical Student: OK, and have you had a cough?
Patient: Uh, no, I don't think so.
Medical Student: Just wondering if you could tell me a little bit about your diet?

Patient: Oh, well my mom always like makes me a lunch like I'll have like a sandwich for lunch with like you know ham and cheese or something. I'll usually have like cereal for breakfast and my mom makes dinner. It's usually like meat like potatoes and vegetables or something. I think it's like pretty normal.
Medical Student: OK, And. Were there anything, was there anything that you tried besides the rest to make those symptoms go away?
Patient: Yeah, yeah, like I will if I if I try to run fast. Like I, kinda can't breathe anymore.
Medical Student: and how long does it take for the breathing difficulty to go away?
Patient: If I stop doing like the thing I'm doing it, I I don't know not very long like couple of minutes.
Medical Student: OK, and have you been having any episodes of shortness of breath at night time?
Patient: Oh no. No, mostly like gym class like I said.
Medical Student: OK um. And, uh, any fevers or chills?
Patient: No.
Medical Student: Um, so anything like like allergies like runny nose or really itchy eyes with maybe some like um tearing?
Patient: When I was around the cats, yeah. But not the other times.
Medical Student: OK, and how about any nausea or vomiting?
Patient: No.
Medical Student: Um, so anything like like allergies like runny nose or really itchy eyes with maybe some like um tearing?
Patient: When I was around the cats, yeah. But not the other times.
Medical Student: Do you find like in the spring or fall time or even summer that you get um like dry eyes or really itchy eyes or runny nose?
Patient: Yeah, I just thought like I had a cold, but I guess like I usually feel like that in the springtime.
Medical Student: Have you had any thoughts of hurting or harming yourself?
Patient: No.
Medical Student: Have you been having any episodes of shortness of breath at night time?
Patient: Oh no. No, mostly like gym class like I said.
Medical Student: And then how about, uh, have you been having any night sweats?
Patient: What's that?
Medical Student: So, uh, overnight when you're sleeping you wake up with either your like pajamas drenched, or your your sheets drenched drenched from sweating.
Patient: Oh no.
Medical Student: OK, any urinary problems?
Patient: Uh, like. No, no.
Medical Student: OK, and how about any nausea or vomiting?
Patient: No.
Medical Student: Um, so anything like like allergies like runny nose or really itchy eyes with maybe some like um tearing?
Patient: When I was around the cats, yeah. But not the other times.

Patient: Oh, another time, like I went to my friends house and they had like a bunch of cats I I felt like I got wheezy sound and I felt like that time it took longer for for the breathing to get easier like I had to leave.
Medical Student: OK, so you've noticed changes to to your breathing sounds? Like you've had noisy breathing before?
Patient: Yeah, mostly just with the cat.
